>The other thing that you probably mean is that when the DES will not
>be reapproved for another five years (the next examnatiion is due in
>1998, I thiink), it was proposed that, instead of the DES, there will
>be a new encryption standard that will not be public, but instead
>designed, implemented, and distributed by NSA in tamper-proof modules.
>Even the keys will have to be generated and distributed by NSA.
>
>Some people have voiced concern that NSA might substitute a weaker
>scheme than DES, in particular one that NSA could break, without its
>users knowing about it.  There is some basic discussion about it in
>G. Simmons, "Contemporary Cryptography", IEEE Press 1992, Chapter
>who-remembers, "The DES: Past, Present, and Future.".
